description.value: Serpentine shabti of Amenhotep II: the figure represents the pharaoh wrapped like a mummy with only head and hands emerging; there is no indication of sleeve or collar ends. He wears the royal 'nemes' wig cover with two long lappets at the front and a queue at the back. When coloured, the characteristic stripes of the 'nemes' are alternating yellow and blue. The 'nemes' was made from either dyed leather or possibly even gold with lapis lazuli inlays. On the king's forehead is an upreared cobra, symbol of kingship, and on his chin the long royal beard. In his hands the shabti holds two 'ankh' signs, symbolizing life and, in particular, the desired life after death, thus identifying the figure with the king himself.
